We take the first element and sort it to compare it with the second element.
If both elements or strings are equal, we then delete ith element, else we go to next element.

**Why are we doing i--? :**
```
Okay, lets take an array a= ["abb", "bax", "xab", "axb"]
suppose we start loop, following are the iterations:
loop 1: compare "bax" with "abb", not anagram
loop 2: compare "xab" with "bax", it is anagram and we delete i th(2th) element, i.e, "xab", now array is = ["abb", "bax", "axb"];
            now i is still 2, we increment it by 3. Since 3>sizeof(arr) we get out of the loop.
            See, "bax" and "axb" are still anagram and we are not checking them.
            So while deleting element we decrease size of i, so that we make sure to compare the left elements.
```
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<string> removeAnagrams(vector<string>& words) {
        for(int i = 1;i<words.size();i++){
            string x = words[i];
            sort(x.begin(),x.end());
            string y = words[i-1];
            sort(y.begin(),y.end());
            if(x == y){
                words.erase(words.begin() + i);
                i--;
            }
        }
        return words;
    }
};
```



